            <h1 class="text-5xl font-bold text-slate-900 leading-tight">Sensorial Introduction to Tone Bars</h1>
            <p class="mt-4 text-slate-400 italic">Guide: Elim Lee // April 1st Sprint // AMI Elementary</p>
        </header>

        <section class="material-box">
            <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-2">Material Overview</h3>
            <div class="text-sm text-slate-700 space-y-3">
                <p><strong>Construction:</strong> The tone bars are evenly wide blocks, painted black and white to mimic the keyboard notes on a piano. However, the black keys are not indented; they sit flush in a continuous row.</p>
                <p><strong>Playing Mechanism:</strong> To play, the child pulls out the keys they intend to play by tugging on the plastic base with two fingers. Once pulled forward, the child taps the silver center of the bar with the mallet. The guiding principle is <em>"never louder than lovely."</em></p>
                <p><strong>The Transposer Strip:</strong> A slip of poster paper with Sharpie-written numbers (1-8). It features deliberately blank squares in between some numbers to visually emphasize <strong>Whole Steps</strong>. The strip slides below the pulled-out tone bars like a physical transposer.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="material-box">
            <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-2">Purpose</h3>
            <ul class="text-sm font-medium italic text-slate-600 list-disc ml-5 mb-4 space-y-1">
                <li>To introduce the tone bars and support sensorial exploration of pitch.</li>
                <li>To help the child understand that a major scale may begin on any pitch, as long as the pattern of whole steps and half steps is preserved.</li>
                <li>To provide a bridge between the sensorial experience of sound and abstract musical notation.</li>
                <li>To reinforce awareness of patterns in nature and mathematics through sound.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-2">Prerequisites</h3>
            <ul class="text-sm font-medium italic text-slate-600 list-disc ml-5 mb-4 space-y-1">
                <li>Ability to match and grade the Montessori bells (diatonic major scale).</li>
                <li>Knowledge of: Tetrachord, Diatonic major scale pattern (W-W-H-W-W-W-H), Chromatic scale, Pentatonic scale, and Whole tone scale.</li>
                <li>Familiarity with the staff, especially the treble (G) clef.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-slate-400 mb-2">Materials List</h3>
            <ul class="text-sm font-medium italic text-slate-600 list-disc ml-5 space-y-1">
                <li>Tone bars, arranged chromatically on their board.</li>
                <li>Rubber mallet (soft head to preserve timbre).</li>
                <li>Major scale pattern strip (movable guide showing whole-step/half-step sequence).</li>
                <li>Staff notation card.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2 class="font-sans font-bold text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-amber-600 mb-8 border-b pb-2 italic">Presentation I: Review – Tone Bars & Scale Pattern</h2>

            <div class="action">Lay out tone bars in sequence. Pause.</div>
            <div class="dialogue">"Let’s listen again to our tone bars… do you remember how they rise and fall?"</div>

            <div class="action">Strike two bars, low then high. (Remember: "Never louder than lovely").</div>
            <div class="dialogue">"Low voice, high voice… same pattern as our bells."</div>

            <div class="action">Place major scale pattern strip beside/below the bars.</div>
            <div class="dialogue">"Here’s the secret pattern—whole, whole, half…" (tap strip as you say it)</div>

            <div class="action">Slide the strip to start at different bars.</div>
            <div class="dialogue">"Look—no matter where we begin, the steps stay the same… this is how music builds a major scale."</div>

