                </svg>
                <div class="illustrate-label">Fig 1.2: The "Transposer" logic. Selected bars are pulled forward. Blank squares represent un-played half steps.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="action">Invite child to experiment: shift strip, play.</div>
            <div class="dialogue">"Where else could we start? Try it!"</div>

            <div class="action">Place two different scales side by side. Gesture linking ear to staff card.</div>
            <div class="dialogue">"Same pattern, different home—this is why there are many scales. Your ear knows it before your eye—do you hear the family resemblance?"</div>

            <div class="aside-box text-sm italic text-amber-900 leading-relaxed mt-8">
                <strong>Guide Notes:</strong> Move slowly, give time for the child to absorb the sound differences. Use minimal words—allow the sensorial experience of pitch to dominate. Children may spontaneously sing along; welcome this but keep it exploratory, not performative. Encourage repetition until the child shows satisfaction or curiosity leads elsewhere.
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="mt-12">
            <h2 class="font-sans font-bold text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-slate-400 mb-6 border-b pb-2">Side Notes & Extensions</h2>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
                <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-800 mb-2">Points of Interest</h4>
                    <ul class="text-xs text-slate-600 space-y-2 list-disc ml-4">
                        <li>Discovering that every culture organizes sound into scales.</li>
                        <li>Feeling the difference between starting a scale on C vs. G vs. F.</li>
                        <li>Comparing the sound of pentatonic vs. diatonic vs. whole-tone.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-800 mb-2">Key Vocabulary</h4>
                    <ul class="text-xs text-slate-600 space-y-2 list-disc ml-4">
                        <li><strong>Scale:</strong> an ordered set of notes, arranged by pitch.</li>
                        <li><strong>Whole step:</strong> the distance of two half steps.</li>
                        <li><strong>Half step:</strong> the smallest step in Western music (e.g., E–F).</li>
                        <li><strong>Tonic:</strong> the note a scale begins and ends on (home).</li>
                        <li><strong>Tetrachord:</strong> a group of four notes spanning a perfect fourth.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-800 mb-2">Fun Facts</h4>
                    <ul class="text-xs text-slate-600 space-y-2 list-disc ml-4">
                        <li>Ancient Greek philosopher Pythagoras studied vibrating strings to discover mathematical ratios behind scales.</li>
                        <li>The major scale pattern (W-W-H-W-W-W-H) appears in countless folk songs worldwide.</li>
                        <li>Birdsongs often follow pentatonic or diatonic fragments!</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-slate-50 p-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-100">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-sm text-slate-800 mb-2">Control of Error & Accommodations</h4>
                    <ul class="text-xs text-slate-600 space-y-2 list-disc ml-4">
                        <li>If a child misplaces the strip, the sound will not resolve to a proper scale (auditory error).</li>
                        <li>Sensitive ears: allow softer mallet use.</li>
                        <li>Safety: remind not to bang bars too hard to avoid damage.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

